    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves on the bottom of the stems, while the top ones are still green, is a classic sign of a nutrient issue, often related to mobile nutrients like nitrogen. It's very common, and you can fix it by giving your tomato plants a good dose of fertilizer, perhaps one that is higher in nitrogen to get those lower leaves back to vibrant green. You might want to start with a balanced, slow-release organic fertilizer to avoid shocking the roots, which is much safer than trying to suddenly dump a pile of raw, aggressive fertilizer on them. Remember, even the most well-meaning gardener can accidentally overfeed, so start small, especially if your soil is already rich.",
      "source": "target",
