    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay lime makes sense. but i've also noticed some weird holes in the leaves lately, and sometimes it looks like bits of the plant are just... gone. like something was eating them overnight. is that just more of the nutrient stuff or could something else be stealing the nutrients from the plant?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Holes and missing bits of plant tissue sound less like a nutrient deficiency and much more like a pest problem, which is a whole different kind of sneaky trouble! You might be dealing with some hungry little critters, perhaps slugs, snails, or even certain types of leaf-chewing caterpillars. These pests are the little scavengers that are definitely stealing the plant's energy, much like a tiny, hungry band of root-gnawing goblins would be stealing the best bits of a treasure hoard!\n\nIf you see actual holes, you need to inspect the undersides of the leaves very closely. If you see tiny trails or slime, slugs or snails are likely the culprits. For a quick fix, you can try setting up beer traps—a shallow dish of beer near the plants will lure them in, and they'll drown, which is a very effective, if slightly messy, way to deal with them. If it's caterpillars, you might need to handpick them or use some targeted, organic insecticidal soap.",
